# Absolute Paths for Cross-Repo References (REMITechnician)

This repo lives at `/Users/jacegalloway/Documents/codebases/REMITechnician`. Cross-repo content (the Docs workspace, sibling REMI apps) lives elsewhere on disk and is **not** reachable with a bare relative path from here.

## Hard rule

When writing prompt text, plan content, dev-log entries, or any string that may be read in a different workspace, refer to cross-repo files using their **absolute path**.

| Repo | Absolute prefix |
|------|-----------------|
| Docs | `/Users/jacegalloway/Documents/Docs/...` |
| REMIBackend | `/Users/jacegalloway/Documents/codebases/REMIBackend/...` |
| REMITechnician | `/Users/jacegalloway/Documents/codebases/REMITechnician/...` |
| REMIDashboard | `/Users/jacegalloway/Documents/codebases/REMIDashboard/...` |
| REMICustomer | `/Users/jacegalloway/Documents/codebases/REMICustomer/...` |

The most common offender is `docs/pdf-implementation-plans/...` — that folder is in the Docs workspace, NOT here. Use `/Users/jacegalloway/Documents/Docs/docs/pdf-implementation-plans/...` instead.

## What stays relative

Do **not** absolutize:

- This repo's own internal paths (e.g., `docs/implementation-plans/foo.md`, `app/...`, `src/...`) — those resolve correctly from this workspace root.
- Markdown links like `[text](plans/foo.md)` — internal docs nav must stay relative to the source file.
- URL-encoded site URLs (`?f=pdf-implementation-plans%2F...`).

## Automation

- **Script:** `scripts/absolutize-doc-paths.sh` rewrites bare `docs/pdf-implementation-plans/...` references to the absolute Docs path. Run manually:
  ```
  ./scripts/absolutize-doc-paths.sh                # scan whole repo
  ./scripts/absolutize-doc-paths.sh path/to/file   # process one file
  ./scripts/absolutize-doc-paths.sh --check        # exit 1 if any drift
  ```
- **Hook:** `.cursor/hooks/absolutize-paths.sh` runs on every `afterFileEdit` (Write/Edit). Any markdown/mdc file you touch with a bare cross-repo ref is auto-rewritten before the next tool call. Wired in `.cursor/hooks.json`.

The hook is a safety net — write absolute paths up front when you can. Inline absolute paths are self-explanatory to humans reading the doc later.
